[2] Logistical challenges
Date: Tue 27 Nov 2012
Source: The Guardian [edited]
http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development-professionals-network/2012/nov/27/immunisation-campaigns-vaccines-africa


A yellow fever outbreak in Sudan's Darfur region shows the difficulties faced by immunisation teams operating in some of Africa's most remote and under-developed regions.

A yellow fever vaccination campaign has began in 4 of those regions, targeting some 2.4 million people. Darfur is still affected by serious instability since conflict broke out there in 2003 -- hundreds of thousands of people have been displaced, the region is impoverished and has very basic infrastructure. One of the biggest obstacles is keeping the 'cold chain' intact; in Darfur temperatures can often reach well above 40C [104 F] and vaccines can become obsolete [ineffective] if they are not kept in a temperature range of about 2-8C [36 - 46 F].

"It's a real challenge," says Dr Anshu Banerjee the World Health Organisation's representative in Sudan. "In Darfur we're travelling miles from urban centres along poor roads. Most places we visit have no mains electricity; often we can't find batteries or even fuel for generators so keeping fridges running for the vaccines is very difficult."

At the lowest level of village distribution, in the absence of fridges the vaccines are usually transported in cool boxes with ice packs inside, either being carried on foot or on the back of motorbikes. In the most extreme cases, health care workers may have to walk for up to 3 days carrying these boxes, visiting families door-to-door. Although Banerjee says Sudan currently has a good reputation and donor support for maintaining the cold chain, significant losses can be incurred especially if a break in the chain begins higher up in the distribution network.

Vaccines lose their 'integrity' if the cold chain is interrupted. "Both the patient and the health care system suffer" says Alexo Dodoo, director of the International Centre for Pharmaco-vigilance based in Accra, Ghana. "Patients may experience adverse reactions to the bad vaccines and the immunisation programme doesn't know whether that's due to a faulty product or because quality and efficacy have been compromised."

Over the border in Chad innovative ways to keep the cold chain intact are being tested. UNICEF and the health ministry are launching a programme of solar powered fridges which remove the need for mains electricity, wiring and plug sockets, or a reliable source of fuel for generators.

The 1st solar fridges are on order from the US and UK and should arrive in December [2012]. "We're hoping to re-equip some 800 health centres across the whole of Chad by 2016" says Clement Njumo, immunisations specialist at UNICEF Chad. "Each 100 litre fridge costs around [USD] 5000 but in the long run we'll definitely be saving money as fewer vaccines will be wasted and we won't have to buy petrol anymore."

UNICEF say they've already been using solar fridges to great effect in similar vaccination campaigns in Sierra Leone, with some types of fridges even being capable of sending out signals and SMS messages when the temperature varies more than 2C [36 F] from the perfect level.

"It's a real problem for us if children have walked for hours with their parents to the vaccination centre only to find that there are none left because of these bottlenecks in supply," says Hector Calderon, head of communications for Unicef Chad. "Sometimes parents won't return for a 2nd time -- that's a child's life and ultimately we need to cover 100 per cent of children to be successful in these campaigns."

Further research is going on at the level of the drugs companies to develop so-called 'thermo-stable' vaccines which are less sensitive to the extreme temperatures. But tackling the practical problems surrounding the distribution networks is just one issue -- lack of awareness and low turn-out for immunisation campaigns is also a serious challenge in these isolated regions.

[Byline: Celeste Hicks]

